§19. terrorem: before this word the definition of pudor (αἰσχύνη) given as a subdivision of φόβος by Diog. L. and Stobaeus must have fallen out, as the words ex quo fit, ut pudorem rubor...con- sequatur also serve to indicate. Cf. Stob. l.c. ἔκπληξις δὲ φόβος ἐξ ἀσυνήθους φαν- τασίας· αἰσχύνη δὲ φόβος ἀδοξίας, and similarly Diog. L. l.c. and Andron l.c. Hence Sff. conjectures pudorem metum dedecoris accounting sor the error on the theory that the copyist’s eye strayed from the ending of laboris to that of dedecoris. Wes. Em. 111 p. 3 sought a participle ending like the following concutientem. e.g. calefacientem: similarly Bai., ed. Tauchn., conj. pudorem metum sanguinem
